# set seed for consistency across sessions
set.seed(541)

# additional random changes across all variables in dataframe
attitude_2 <- attitude |> 
  rbind(attitude |> 
          mutate(across(everything(), ~ (.x * rnorm(nrow(attitude), 0, 1))))) |> 
  rbind(attitude |> 
          mutate(across(everything(), ~ (.x * rnorm(nrow(attitude), 0, 0.1))))) |> 
  rbind(attitude |> 
          mutate(across(everything(), ~ (.x * rnorm(nrow(attitude), 0, 0.01)))))


# standardization and more random changes to make lines more random
attitude_2 <- attitude_2 |> 
  rbind(attitude_2 |> 
          mutate(across(everything(), ~ (.x * rnorm(nrow(attitude), 0, .1))))
  ) |> 
  mutate(across(everything(), ~ (.x * -1))) |> # rotate
  mutate(across(everything(), ~ (.x - max(.x)))) # standardize


# creation of the artwork
attitude_2 |>

        plot.background = element_rect(fill = "black"))

Museum Description

The sun has always been a part of humanityâs history, and its no wonder why we find sunsets so soothing to the soul. Thus, this art piece is meant to replicate the feeling of a peaceful end to the day, and the wonder of the beginning of the night.

Code Choices

The extra rows created from rbind are meant to create âlayersâ on the sun, and the multiplication by -1 is meant to rotate the image to make it more presentable. The standardization is meant to condense all of the lines together so that it forms a more cohesive image.

## The code is from https://art-from-code.netlify.app/day-1/session-4/
sample_canva2 <- function(seed = NULL, n = 4) {
  
  if(!is.null(seed)) set.seed(seed)
  sample(ggthemes::canva_palettes, 1)[[1]] |>
    (\(x) colorRampPalette(x)(n))()  
}

transform_to_curl_space <- function(x, y, frequency = 6, octaves = 10) {
  curl_noise(
    generator = fracture,
    noise = gen_simplex,
    fractal = fbm,
    octaves = octaves,
    frequency = frequency,
    x = x,
    y = y
  )
}


define_worley_cells <- function(x, y, frequency = 2, octaves = 6) {
  fracture(
    noise = gen_worley,
    fractal = billow,
    octaves = octaves,
    frequency = frequency,
    value = "cell",
    x = x,
    y = y
  ) |>
    rank() |> 
    normalise()
}

simplex_noise <- function(x, y, frequency = .085, octaves = 10) {
  fracture(
    noise = gen_simplex,
    fractal = ridged,
    octaves = octaves,
    frequency = frequency,
    x = x,
    y = y
  ) |>
    normalise()
}

ice_floe <- function(seed) {

  set.seed(seed)
  
  grid <- long_grid(
    x = seq(0, 1, length.out = 2000),
    y = seq(0, 1, length.out = 2000)
  )
  
  coords <- transform_to_curl_space(grid$x, grid$y)
  
  grid |>
    mutate(
      cells = define_worley_cells(coords$x, coords$y),
      paint = simplex_noise(x + cells, y + cells),
      paint = normalise(paint)
    ) |>
    as.array(value = paint)
}


shaded_ice_floe <- function(seed) {
  
  art <- ice_floe(seed)
  
  height_shade(
    heightmap = art,
    texture = sample_canva2(seed, 4)
  ) |>
    add_shadow(
      shadowmap = ray_shade(
        heightmap = art, 
        sunaltitude = 60, 
        sunangle = 135,
        multicore = TRUE, 
        zscale = .005
      ), 
      max_darken = 0.01
    ) |>
    plot_map()
}

shaded_ice_floe(12345)

Museum Description

The sickly spread of the disease from the left-hand corner infiltrates the healthy cells, spreading chaos and despair among the cells still remaining. The cancer is almost moving in a insidious manner, spreading its tendrils to capture the rest of the cells.

Code Choices

  • Changed the frequency and octaves which changed the size of the âcell wallsâ
  • The sun angle I chose as 135 for the light to come from the bottom right Sun altitude maybe 60 for the light to come at an angle since there were too many âmountainsâ in the way
  • Made the transform to curl space have a high frequency to generate more âcellsâ
  • Made the worley noise to 2 since it seemed to generate the area within the cells, and I chose a good middle ground between too much ânoiseâ within each cell and not too much noise.
  • Limited the number of colors to 4 in order to make it more minimalistic.
  • The simplex noise seems to affect the height, so I wanted something with more valleys by making the frequency lower to 0.085.
